that regularly changed hands between the Scots and the English. Also from any of the places called Berwick in Dorset and elsewhere, Berrick in Oxfordshire, Barwick in Norfolk and Yorkshire, or Barricks in High Easter, Essex. This could also be a topographic name for someone who lived ‘(at the) outlying grange’, from Middle English <i>ber(e)wik</i> ‘outlying grange or farm, demesne farm’ (Old English <i>berewīc</i> ‘barley farm’)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Gilbert de Berwick was born in 1295, in Winterslow, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Knight Richard de Berwick II, was 25 and his mother, Mrs Ricard de Berwick II, was 24. He married Mrs. Isabel de Berwick about 1313, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 2 November 1361, in Berwick St James, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1295–2 November 1361":"1295–2. november 1361","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1298–Female":"1298–Surnud","1312–1362":"1312–1362","1339–1400":"umbes1339–1400","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1312":"1312","1400":"1400","2 November 1361":"2. november 1361","1298":"1298","about 1313":"umbes 1313","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1361":"1361","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1339":"umbes 1339","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Ingli